courses.learning_outcomes:
After taking this course, students should be able to:
1. Compare and contrast different schools of thoughts in analyzing and explaining urban developments;
2. Identify the specificities of urban development in Hong Kong vis-à-vis urban studies theories generated from other urban contexts;
3. Evaluate the roles of the state, the market and civil society in shaping urban transformations;
4. Identify the key elements of urban form and the forces of its transformation; and
5. Develop independent and critical thinking in applying theories to analyse concrete urban phenomena.

After taking this course, students are expected to:

* apply urban studies, planning and design theories and analytical tools in the field study;
* compare and contrast context-based societal issues and formulate related research questions;
* reflect on the diversified interests of various local stakeholders;
* analyse urban issues with reference to theories and international practices; and
* formulate practical solutions considering local constraints and opportunities.

(1) To explain the historical, economic and geopolitical background of the Belt and Road Initiative;

(2) To analyze economic, social, environmental, cultural and political forces, structures and processes associated with the Belt and Road Initiative;

(3) To evaluate the built environment and urban issues of Eurasian cities and how these may be improved by appropriate integration into the Belt and Road infrastructure;

(4) To apply Hong Kong’s world-class urban management practices to help the Belt and Road countries to maximize the benefits of network externality effects;

(5) To simulate and predict multi-scale spatial economic and urban outcomes of the Belt and Road infrastructure investments.

(6) To synthesize intercultural and global perspectives and to recommend ways to foster international cooperation, cultural diversity and integration.

After taking this course, students should be able to:

1. Understand the basic framework of urban planning and design in China;

2. Understand the basic planning standards and guidelines in planning practice in mainland China;

3. Compare the Hong Kong planning system and practices with mainland China;

4. Find planning information and keep track of the current planning topics in mainland China and understand the gist of the issues;

5. Build up multi-dimensional skills and confidence in future planning communication.

After taking this course, students should be able to:

1. recognize the inter-connectedness of various sectors in urban development and the importance of integrated and holistic thinking in pursuing urban sustainability;
2. explain and analyze how socioeconomic factors affect the sustainability of a place;
3. generalize existing and emerging approaches to urban sustainability;
4. compare and contrast the roles of the government, the private sector and the civil society in moving towards urban sustainability; and

5. develop a capacity to diagnose urban sustainability issues and offer plausible solutions.

After taking this course, students should be able to:

1. Compare and contrast patterns of spatial arrangements of firm and households in cities;
2. Identify externalities arising from the spatial arrangements of cities;
3. Develop independent and critical thinking in evaluating existing related urban economic issues; and

4. Use economic concepts to formulate appropriate public policies to address urban issues.

After taking this course, students should be able to :

1. understand urban design as a multidisciplinary field;
2. recognize the contribution of urban design to the creation or enhancement of urban places;
3. develop creative sensitivity for the qualities of place;
4. analyze and evaluate how urban design projects can facilitate and shape community based urban processes;
5. compare and contrast concepts and positions in urban design and place theory; and

6. reflect on contemporary opportunities and challenges of urban design.

After taking the course, students should be able to:

1. Gain knowledge of various concepts, standards and typologies of comparative urbanism;
2. Critically engage developmentalist perspectives when comparing cities;
3. Develop methods and frameworks to explain differences and similarities between urban forms, experiences and spaces;
4. Analyze the complex ways in which various configurations of urban life relate to specific historical events, cultural influences, institutional effects, political agency and informal processes.

After taking this course, students are expected to:

•apply urban studies, planning and design theories and analytical tools in the field study;
•compare and contrast context-based societal issues and formulate related research questions;
•reflect on the diversified interests of various local stakeholders;
•analyse urban issues with reference to theories and international practices; and

•formulate practical solutions considering local constraints and opportunities.

After taking this course, students will be able to:

• Synthesise, analyse, compare and contrast various urban studies theories;
• Evaluate and reflect on the applicability of the theories learned in the urban context of Hong Kong and beyond;
• Advance and develop their own strands of thoughts on urban development so that they can review urban affairs critically; and

• To theorize and formulate principles from the study materials for life-long learning and practice.

After taking this course, students are expected to:

•Compare and contrast various approaches to the provision of housing as one of the human rights or as part of the market mechanisms;
•identify, analyse and explain factors related to housing provision and behavior;
•reflect on the various socio-economic, environmental, physical and governance aspects of housing provision at different geographical levels;
•generanlize and reflect on the theoretical issues related to housing provision; and

•develop capacity in creating and designing a sustainable housing policy.

After taking this course, students are expected to:

•understand current challenges in urban transport;
•understand the sustainable planning process;
•identify the economic indicators, social indicators, and environmental indicators for transport planning;
•analyze proposals for individual cities and communities; and

•evaluate transport policy recommendations.

After taking the course, students are expected to

- Understand the core concepts and theories of urban regeneration;
- Understand the theories, functions and opportunities of land use planning, architectural conservation, landscape improvement and urban design in the process of Urban Regeneration;
- Apply theoretical and practical perspectives to analyze the multi-disciplinary function involved in urban regeneration cases;
- Analyze and evaluate the interests and concerns of different stakeholders and the disputes in the role of the URA and the Government in the process of Urban Regeneration; and

- Understand the impact of Urban Regeneration on the community and the society at large; and

- Generate own perspectives and interest in the subject of urban regeneration, land use planning, architectural conservation, urban and landscape design, and social impact of the process.

